Computes the negative log likelihood of an underlying continuous distribution from binned data.

Source: R/mle.R
bin_log_likelihood.Rd

From: https://stats.stackexchange.com/a/68238/97417

Usage

bin_log_likelihood(theta, cdf, counts, bin_lower, bin_upper, ...)

Arguments

theta

parameters for distribution

cdf

the cdf function (pnorm, pgamma, punif)

counts

the histogram bins

bin_lower

the lower bounds for the histogram bins (a, b]

bin_upper

the upper bounds for the histogram bins (a, b]

...

Additional parameters to pass into cdf

Value

the negative log-likelihood to be minimized

Examples

set.seed(100);
x <- rnorm(1000, sd = 5)
bin.x <- observations_to_histogram(x)

bin_log_likelihood(
  theta = c(0, 4),
  cdf = pnorm,
  counts = bin.x$histogram_data,
  bin_lower = bin.x$interval_start,
  bin_upper = bin.x$interval_end
  )
#> [1] 3137.2

dist_optim <- DEoptim::DEoptim(
  fn = bin_log_likelihood,
  cdf = pnorm,
  counts = bin.x$histogram_data,
  bin_lower = bin.x$interval_start,
  bin_upper = bin.x$interval_end,
  lower = c(min(bin.x$interval_start), 0.01),
  upper = c(max(bin.x$interval_end), 10),
  control = list(
    trace = TRUE,
    itermax = 500
    )
  )
